//www.academia.edu/download/32410119/Cox-Soundcultures.pdf</a>","favorite_count":"0","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Jan 08 17:09:46 +0000 2020","id_str":"1214957378174672905","full_text":"Hardcore conversation about Deleuze and Guattari going on behind me on the bus. Unusual.","favorite_count":"11","retweet_count":"2"},{"created_at":"Tue Dec 24 08:57:38 +0000 2019","id_str":"1209397709964222464","full_text":"Just learned that my dad kept some of the wonderful 10p-a-sheet bargain rack wrapping paper I bought as a teenager. Spot the hidden message <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1209397709964222464-EMikxDaWkAEv8-e.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1209397709964222464-EMikxDaWkAEv8-e.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Mon Dec 16 18:46:10 +0000 2019","id_str":"1206646715786371073","full_text":"Also the photographer generally doesn't have the right grip on what we'd label as the objects in the photo - they're at an angle, or in the corner, or blurry. Rectangles make this more likely to happen maybe, as the symmetry is so easily broken?","favorite_count":"1","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Dec 16 18:46:09 +0000 2019","id_str":"1206646713982869511","full_text":"There are some competing geometric orders, tendrils-of-mess style, but not enough to be a mess. Just looks dull instead somehow? <a href=\"https://www.ribbonfarm.com/2017/01/05/tendrils-of-mess-in-our-brains/\">https://www.ribbonfarm.com/2017/01/05/tendrils-of-mess-in-our-brains/</a>","favorite_count":"1","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Dec 16 18:46:09 +0000 2019","id_str":"1206646711818575872","full_text":"I was scrolling through these last night and now I really want to know the @literalbanana take on the aesthetics of uninteresting photographs. Lots of rectangles in there!<br><br><a href=\"https://twitter.com/UninterestingP4/status/1160959247439581186\">https://twitter.com/UninterestingP4/status/1160959247439581186</a>","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Dec 05 21:50:13 +0000 2019","id_str":"1202706768943599619","full_text":"I will definitely be a resident at this and will do my best to manage some thinking too :) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/SenseWorkshop/status/1202696185481433088\">https://twitter.com/SenseWorkshop/status/1202696185481433088</a>","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Nov 29 09:03:24 +0000 2019","id_str":"1200339464914178053","full_text":"This beetle knows how to do it <a href=\"https://twitter.com/drossbucket/status/1170587265480974336\">https://twitter.com/drossbucket/status/1170587265480974336</a> <a href=\"https://twitter.com/Rainmaker1973/status/1200309727353327617\">https://twitter.com/Rainmaker1973/status/1200309727353327617</a>","favorite_count":"1","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sat Jun 11 10:08:09 +0000 2022","id_str":"1535564536299851776","full_text":"57. TIL that if you convolve the Hermite polynomial H_n with a Gaussian, you get x^n<br> <a href=\"https://twitter.com/sigfpe/status/1535464531329048576\">https://twitter.com/sigfpe/status/1535464531329048576</a>","favorite_count":"1","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Jun 09 16:17:30 +0000 2022","id_str":"1534932712439554059","full_text":"56. TIL about the lemniscate sine and cosine functions<br><br>Well, at least I learned that they exist <a href=\"https://twitter.com/johncarlosbaez/status/1534925308712787969\">https://twitter.com/johncarlosbaez/status/1534925308712787969</a>","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sun Jun 05 20:36:10 +0000 2022","id_str":"1533548256009113602","full_text":"<div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1533548256009113602-FUhB6N1WIAACN9m.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1533548256009113602-FUhB6N1WIAACN9m.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"0","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sun Jun 05 20:31:15 +0000 2022","id_str":"1533547019138105345","full_text":"<div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1533547019138105345-FUhAByjXwAAVNOB.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1533547019138105345-FUhAByjXwAAVNOB.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"0","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sun Jun 05 20:18:44 +0000 2022","id_str":"1533543868880375808","full_text":"More Brian Cantwell Smith... just dug up this talk on digitality, not far in but interesting so far<br><br>He talks about digitality being undertheorised in one of his youtube talks and I wished he'd expanded on that, this seems promising<br><br> <a href=\"https://www.c-span.org/video/?184429-1/digital-future-meaning-digital\">https://www.c-span.org/video/?184429-1/digital-future-meaning-digital</a>","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sun Jun 05 08:18:27 +0000 2022","id_str":"1533362601782087681","full_text":"@m_ashcroft @nosilverv @JakeOrthwein still trying <a href=\"https://drossbucket.com/2022/06/04/lets-try-and-understand-brian-cantwell-smith-again/\">https://drossbucket.com/2022/06/04/lets-try-and-understand-brian-cantwell-smith-again/</a>","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sat Jun 04 16:46:57 +0000 2022","id_str":"1533128181485543425","full_text":"New post ‚Äì partly a review of Brian Cantwell Smith‚Äôs ‚ÄòThe Promise of Artificial Intelligence‚Äô, partly another attempt to understand what he‚Äôs on about generally<br><br><a href=\"https://drossbucket.com/2022/06/04/lets-try-and-understand-brian-cantwell-smith-again/\">https://drossbucket.com/2022/06/04/lets-try-and-understand-brian-cantwell-smith-again/</a>","favorite_count":"6","retweet_count":"2"},{"created_at":"Sat Nov 16 17:03:42 +0000 2019","id_str":"1195749292989960197","full_text":"@Meaningness One thing we'd go back and forward on was how much detail to put in the wiki steps. Not enough and a new person has no hope of following them, too much and you can get stuck in following-the-steps mode without developing an understanding of what you're doing.","favorite_count":"7","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sat Nov 16 16:55:16 +0000 2019","id_str":"1195747172374978562","full_text":"@Meaningness ... or for a GUI we'd make red background with PROD written on them.<br><br>If something was particularly bad if it went wrong we'd get a second person to check the steps.","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Nov 12 17:16:09 +0000 2019","id_str":"1194302874634924033","full_text":"@DRMacIver oh and the other thing I do a lot is just give up. I look for things with the right level of 'lock' where I'm near to understanding but not there yet. If I don't feel like I'm near having a lock yet I don't bother. Being and Time can wait :)","favorite_count":"1","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Nov 12 17:15:26 +0000 2019","id_str":"1194302695739445248","full_text":"@DRMacIver Or for Origin of Objects, I found the one thing in the damn book I could get my head round (his 'middle distance' examples) and worked outwards from there","favorite_count":"1","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sun Nov 10 20:46:47 +0000 2019","id_str":"1193631108174405634","full_text":"*cough* @Meaningness *cough*","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sun Nov 10 20:46:29 +0000 2019","id_str":"1193631032823685120","full_text":"Reblogging this because we're still trying to understand bits of On the Origin of Objects in the comments... please come and join in if you actually understand this book!<br><br><a href=\"https://drossbucket.wordpress.com/2019/10/24/the-middle-distance/\">https://drossbucket.wordpress.com/2019/10/24/the-middle-distance/</a>","favorite_count":"18","retweet_count":"2"},{"created_at":"Thu Oct 24 18:06:27 +0000 2019","id_str":"1187430164235542533","full_text":"Follow-up post on Brian Cantwell Smith's idea of 'the middle distance': the intermediate space between direct causal coupling (e.g. a thermostat) and complete causal irrelevance (ungrounded statements about bananas)<br><a href=\"https://drossbucket.wordpress.com/2019/10/24/the-middle-distance/\">https://drossbucket.wordpress.com/2019/10/24/the-middle-distance/</a>","favorite_count":"7","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Wed Oct 23 18:20:56 +0000 2019","id_str":"1187071424307122177","full_text":"I've had to suffer this earworm while writing the post, so now you get to too :)<br><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=j5C6X9vOEkU\">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=j5C6X9vOEkU</a>","favorite_count":"1","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Oct 23 18:20:56 +0000 2019","id_str":"1187071422667071489","full_text":"Previously discussed here: <a href=\"https://twitter.com/drossbucket/status/1134521173335785472\">https://twitter.com/drossbucket/status/1134521173335785472</a> (in the replies of a non-pretend literal banana)","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Oct 23 18:20:56 +0000 2019","id_str":"1187071420700004354","full_text":"üçå‚òéÔ∏è: new post tracing back the origins of the 'cognitive decoupling' idea to a 1987 paper on pretending that a banana is a phone <a href=\"https://drossbucket.wordpress.com/2019/10/23/cognitive-decoupling-and-banana-phones/\">https://drossbucket.wordpress.com/2019/10/23/cognitive-decoupling-and-banana-phones/</a>","favorite_count":"15","retweet_count":"4"},{"created_at":"Fri Oct 11 18:34:00 +0000 2019","id_str":"1182726054554882050","full_text":"@xuenay @Meaningness I did read *Thinking* (without having read EY) around 2010, and swallowed it uncritically, so I'm in no position to crow at anyone else for doing that now :)","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Oct 11 18:30:33 +0000 2019","id_str":"1182725189471211521","full_text":"@xuenay @Meaningness ... but was it actually all that popular a topic, or just what was in the air ~2008 (like atheism)? I certainly don't see that much of it there any more, just lots of AI.","favorite_count":"0","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Oct 11 17:32:31 +0000 2019","id_str":"1182710582874648576","full_text":"Lots more interesting background on this paper and other recent criticism of the 'Type 1'/'Type 2' split in @xuenay's post: <a href=\"https://www.lesswrong.com/s/ZbmRyDN8TCpBTZSip/p/HbXXd2givHBBLxr3d\">https://www.lesswrong.com/s/ZbmRyDN8TCpBTZSip/p/HbXXd2givHBBLxr3d</a>","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Oct 11 17:32:30 +0000 2019","id_str":"1182710580135768065","full_text":"E.g. bat and ball answer is intentional (a 'Type 2' trait) - you're trying to answer the question. But also uncontrollable ('Type 1') - you get the stupid 10 cents answer whether you like it or not. <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1182710580135768065-EGnU_PeX4AI7iIW.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1182710580135768065-EGnU_PeX4AI7iIW.png\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Oct 11 17:32:25 +0000 2019","id_str":"1182710558140915712","full_text":"'The Mythical Number Two' - <a href=\"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/323998611_The_Mythical_Number_Two\">https://www.researchgate.net/publication/323998611_The_Mythical_Number_Two</a> - via @xuenay<br><br>Wish I'd found this paper before writing my bat and ball post! Splits out distinctions that have been lumped under 'System 1'/'System 2' (or more recently 'Type 1'/'Type 2')","favorite_count":"11","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Sun Oct 06 17:44:36 +0000 2019","id_str":"1180901685067239424","full_text":"I've been thinking about the alethiometer for a while now as a good symbol of something like the preformal - formal - postformal transition. But looks like Pullman's just straight out going there, I don't even have to make it up myself.","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sun Oct 06 17:43:43 +0000 2019","id_str":"1180901463075311618","full_text":"A German philosopher has killed God. Lyra's estranged from her daemon and in full-blown nihilist despair. The government's on a legibility kick. There's a new postmodern way to read the alethiometer.","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sun Oct 06 17:43:11 +0000 2019","id_str":"1180901328349995008","full_text":"Anyone else reading The Secret Commonwealth? Pullman's been reading The Master and his Emissary (there's a quote from him on the front of my copy) and it's not subtle. Really enjoying it so far.","favorite_count":"8","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sat Aug 31 18:14:49 +0000 2019","id_str":"1167863325939523585","full_text":"I've learned that Bristol is complete amateur hour for bridges and I should be thinking about the Hamburg Bridge Problem: <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_bridges_in_Hamburg\">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_bridges_in_Hamburg</a> <a href=\"https://twitter.com/drossbucket/status/1144695285102387202\">https://twitter.com/drossbucket/status/1144695285102387202</a> <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1167863325939523585-EDUVfMFUwAEMi50.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1167863325939523585-EDUVfMFUwAEMi50.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sun Aug 18 17:49:31 +0000 2019","id_str":"1163145915412164609","full_text":"Short post on messy back-of-the-book calculations: <a href=\"https://drossbucket.wordpress.com/2019/08/18/messy-calculations/\">https://drossbucket.wordpress.com/2019/08/18/messy-calculations/</a>","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sat Aug 17 20:38:18 +0000 2019","id_str":"1162826002889920512","full_text":"@michael_nielsen @Meaningness @shapr @wallingf (But of course reading the great practitioners in a field, or about them, might be a better way to impart the same thing.)","favorite_count":"0","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Aug 15 16:59:58 +0000 2019","id_str":"1162046285362470917","full_text":"@DRMacIver oh I just saw your other tweet - obviously you already know that :)","favorite_count":"0","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Aug 05 20:17:05 +0000 2019","id_str":"1158472013062627328","full_text":"Correction for the magic state bit below. Need to think about this more! <a href=\"https://twitter.com/earltcampbell/status/1158468208543842304\">https://twitter.com/earltcampbell/status/1158468208543842304</a>","favorite_count":"0","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Aug 05 19:23:41 +0000 2019","id_str":"1158458571971014657","full_text":"If you were expecting this to end with a satisfying conclusion... um, no, I'm still confused and have lots of questions. Some of which are here! So let me know if you have any helpful insights or references. <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1158458571971014657-EBOr5wSWwAAPFYK.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1158458571971014657-EBOr5wSWwAAPFYK.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Aug 05 19:23:32 +0000 2019","id_str":"1158458535161864192","full_text":"Apparently this has been independently advocated as a measure of information by Brukner and Zeilinger: <a href=\"https://journals.aps.org/prl/abstract/10.1103/PhysRevLett.83.3354\">https://journals.aps.org/prl/abstract/10.1103/PhysRevLett.83.3354</a><br><br>Unfortunately I don't really follow the argument there, so I'm none the wiser.","favorite_count":"1","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Aug 05 19:23:32 +0000 2019","id_str":"1158458533077245952","full_text":"Mathematically this one isn't too bad. The constraint turns out to be that the sum of the squares of the four numbers in the boxes can't be more than half.<br><br>Conceptually... why the hell is it this one?? I don't know.","favorite_count":"0","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Aug 05 19:23:31 +0000 2019","id_str":"1158458530774622209","full_text":"Shannon is only one of a whole family of entropies, the R√©nyi entropies: <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/R%C3%A9nyi_entropy\">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/R%C3%A9nyi_entropy</a><br><br>Wrote some rough notes here that may or may not make sense <a href=\"http://keerlu.github.io/2018/07/16/renyi-entropy.html\">http://keerlu.github.io/2018/07/16/renyi-entropy.html</a><br><br>Anyway the one we want is called the collision entropy.","favorite_count":"1","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Aug 05 19:23:30 +0000 2019","id_str":"1158458527817637888","full_text":"Most obvious choice is the usual one from information theory, linked to the Shannon entropy: <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Entropy_(information_theory)\">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Entropy_(information_theory)</a><br><br>Turns out this isn't the right choice to reproduce QM, though. Instead you want a weirder entropy.","favorite_count":"0","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Aug 05 19:23:30 +0000 2019","id_str":"1158458524743163904","full_text":"Now, there's a fascinating paper by van Enk that builds on the Spekkens toy model, by extending the 'half the information' property to more states: <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/0705.2742\">https://arxiv.org/abs/0705.2742</a><br><br>To do this, you need a good definition of information.","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Aug 05 19:23:29 +0000 2019","id_str":"1158458521630982145","full_text":"There's a very influential toy model that also has this 'half the information' property: <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spekkens_toy_model\">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spekkens_toy_model</a><br><br>Very simple model that reproduces some, but not all, features of quantum theory. It uses just the states on the six corners of the octahedron. So no magic.","favorite_count":"0","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Aug 05 19:23:28 +0000 2019","id_str":"1158458519785545735","full_text":"The interesting one is to do with information. For the toy example, we got definite Y/N answers to all 3 questions. This time the rule is you can only get max half the information. In a weird sense of 'information' I'll get to soon.","favorite_count":"0","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Aug 05 19:23:28 +0000 2019","id_str":"1158458516430118912","full_text":"Even the most magic states are nowhere near as negative as the -¬Ω of the toy example. Why not? Well, there are some constraints.","favorite_count":"0","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Aug 05 19:23:26 +0000 2019","id_str":"1158458509815664641","full_text":"I drew a dodgy picture of the geometry of magic states in the Bloch sphere. The magic ones are outside the octahedron. The further you are from it, the more magic they are. <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1158458509815664641-EBOr2iOWsAUVot9.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1158458509815664641-EBOr2iOWsAUVot9.png\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"1","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Mon Aug 05 19:23:19 +0000 2019","id_str":"1158458480434528257","full_text":"You can learn more from this post by @earltcampbell : <a href=\"https://earltcampbell.com/research/magic-states/\">https://earltcampbell.com/research/magic-states/</a><br><br>(but not from me as I still need to read up on it)","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Aug 05 19:23:18 +0000 2019","id_str":"1158458477909557254","full_text":"Interesting thing I found out while writing the post: quantum computing people call the states with negative entries 'magic states'. Because they contain the magic! I.e., potential for speedup over classical computing.","favorite_count":"0","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Aug 05 19:23:17 +0000 2019","id_str":"1158458473857859586","full_text":"Now for a negative probability example (from the paper). This is the most negative value possible in quantum physics: <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1158458473857859586-EBOr1nVW4AEoowh.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1158458473857859586-EBOr1nVW4AEoowh.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"0","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Aug 05 19:23:15 +0000 2019","id_str":"1158458464185790464","full_text":"For more on how this phase space works, this paper by Wootters is great (he developed a lot of this in the first place): <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/quant-ph/0306135\">https://arxiv.org/abs/quant-ph/0306135</a>","favorite_count":"0","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Aug 05 19:23:14 +0000 2019","id_str":"1158458461199491078","full_text":"Example: |0&gt;. We know the Qz measurement exactly. No idea about the other two. Plot it on 'qubit phase space' like this: <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1158458461199491078-EBOr028XoAEwa1u.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1158458461199491078-EBOr028XoAEwa1u.png\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"0","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Aug 05 19:23:12 +0000 2019","id_str":"1158458451376390144","full_text":"The three measurements Qz, Qx, Qy are something like 'shifted Pauli matrices'.<br><br>Same eigenvectors, but shift the eigenvalues from 1 and -1 to 0 and 1 respectively (for 'no' and 'yes' answers to the questions).","favorite_count":"0","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Aug 05 19:23:12 +0000 2019","id_str":"1158458449233088522","full_text":"This time we are asking the three questions about a qubit state. And the questions become measurements. <br><br>Instead of straight yes/no answers we'll have probabilities of getting yes or no (could've done that before, but this time it's unavoidable).","favorite_count":"0","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Aug 05 19:23:11 +0000 2019","id_str":"1158458447052099584","full_text":"First negative probability thread was surprisingly successful, so I'm going to attempt a thread form of the second post too: <a href=\"https://drossbucket.wordpress.com/2019/08/01/negative-probability-now-with-added-equations/\">https://drossbucket.wordpress.com/2019/08/01/negative-probability-now-with-added-equations/</a><br><br>This one has more physics so is harder to pull off. Going to assume some knowledge of qubits etc.","favorite_count":"7","retweet_count":"2"},{"created_at":"Sat Aug 03 16:24:41 +0000 2019","id_str":"1157688751591739392","full_text":"@Meaningness Wish Twitter let you edit things","favorite_count":"0","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sat Aug 03 16:07:59 +0000 2019","id_str":"1157684548668465152","full_text":"For more information on how all this relates to quantum physics, see my follow up post: <a href=\"https://drossbucket.wordpress.com/2019/08/01/negative-probability-now-with-added-equations/\">https://drossbucket.wordpress.com/2019/08/01/negative-probability-now-with-added-equations/</a><br><br>May try a thread version of that one, too, but that'll be harder work. This is enough for today!","favorite_count":"9","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sat Aug 03 16:07:59 +0000 2019","id_str":"1157684546097356801","full_text":"Now the reason I'm interested in this is the link to quantum physics. This toy model is very similar to phase space for a qubit. In some sense it's slightly 'worse', as -¬Ω is more negative than anything that comes up there. But the simple numbers make it easy to play with.","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sat Aug 03 16:07:58 +0000 2019","id_str":"1157684543752744962","full_text":"Is this trick any use? I really don't know! But I definitely find this breakdown more illuminating than just plugging through the algebra.","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Sat Aug 03 16:07:57 +0000 2019","id_str":"1157684540598554624","full_text":"And it also works for the inconsistent, NNN example! You can see how the bottom left box gets clobbered by the successive -¬ºs, as in my vague motivation at the start. <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1157684540598554624-EBDr8hpXsAAF_NC.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1157684540598554624-EBDr8hpXsAAF_NC.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sat Aug 03 16:07:54 +0000 2019","id_str":"1157684526480592897","full_text":"You can add one of these correction terms for the other two questions as well, ending up with the same as before: <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1157684526480592897-EBDr7xAWwAEHMPV.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1157684526480592897-EBDr7xAWwAEHMPV.png\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sat Aug 03 16:07:51 +0000 2019","id_str":"1157684513423708161","full_text":"Start with the consistent, YNN example, and ask the questions in turn. Before you start you are completely ignorant - probability ¬º of all boxes. After first question you narrow it to two boxes. View this as adding on a correction term: <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1157684513423708161-EBDr7GIW4AAslVV.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1157684513423708161-EBDr7GIW4AAslVV.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sat Aug 03 16:07:48 +0000 2019","id_str":"1157684502308839424","full_text":"So... we penalise bad answers, and, because {first box 0, second box} is particularly bad, it gets clobbered three times instead of just once, driving it negative. That's vague. But I'll outline a precise version.","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sat Aug 03 16:07:48 +0000 2019","id_str":"1157684499909619712","full_text":"Motivating idea: NNN is inconsistent, so all four possible assignments don't work. But {first box 0, second box 0} is *especially* bad. It's the wrong answer to all three questions. Other three boxes are only the wrong answer to one question.","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sat Aug 03 16:07:47 +0000 2019","id_str":"1157684497653075971","full_text":"Now, where that -¬Ω comes from was a bit opaque to me. I mean I could follow the algebra, just didn't have much intuition for how it got there. So I played around for a while and came up with the following.","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sat Aug 03 16:07:47 +0000 2019","id_str":"1157684495610306573","full_text":"Given this, it all works. E.g. for question 1<br><br>P(first 0) = P(first 0, second 0) + P(first 0, second 1) = -¬Ω + ¬Ω = 0<br><br>So answer is N. Same for the others.","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sat Aug 03 16:07:46 +0000 2019","id_str":"1157684491550416898","full_text":"OK, nothing very clever here! Now for an inconsistent set, NNN. Both boxes are in state 0, but... they're also in different states? <br><br>Turns out you can still assign a 'probability' distribution. Sort of. Scare quotes because one 'probability' is negative: <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1157684491550416898-EBDr53dWwAEgZlz.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1157684491550416898-EBDr53dWwAEgZlz.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sat Aug 03 16:07:43 +0000 2019","id_str":"1157684480804626434","full_text":"So, for YNN, we learn that box 1 is definitely in state 0 and box 2 is definitely in state 1. We can represent this as the following probability distribution over possible pairs of states: <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1157684480804626434-EBDr5TAXYAAp_RM.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1157684480804626434-EBDr5TAXYAAp_RM.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sat Aug 03 16:07:41 +0000 2019","id_str":"1157684471405207552","full_text":"Now we ask 3 questions:<br><br>1. Is the first box in state 0?<br>2. Is the second box in state 0?<br>3. Are the boxes both in the same state?<br><br>Obviously these overlap: e.g. to be consistent, if you answered Y to 1. and N to 2., you'd also answer N to 3.","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sat Aug 03 16:07:40 +0000 2019","id_str":"1157684468871835649","full_text":"So we have the following setup (from that post): <br><br>\"a machine produces boxes with (ordererd) pairs of bits in them, each bit viewable through its own door\"","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sat Aug 03 16:07:40 +0000 2019","id_str":"1157684466799845378","full_text":"Instead I'm going to go through an example that shows *how* they work. I got this one from another excellent blog post, by @sigfpe: <a href=\"http://blog.sigfpe.com/2008/04/negative-probabilities.html\">http://blog.sigfpe.com/2008/04/negative-probabilities.html</a><br><br>I like it because the numbers are nice and simple.","favorite_count":"6","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sat Aug 03 16:07:39 +0000 2019","id_str":"1157684464383909893","full_text":"I'm not going to go too much into why people get interested in negative probabilities in the first place. For that (as for so many things) the best place to go is a blog post by @johncarlosbaez: <a href=\"https://johncarlosbaez.wordpress.com/2013/07/19/negative-probabilities/\">https://johncarlosbaez.wordpress.com/2013/07/19/negative-probabilities/</a>","favorite_count":"8","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sat Aug 03 16:07:39 +0000 2019","id_str":"1157684462098046977","full_text":"Negative probability thread!<br><br>(it's the tweet version of this blog post, as an experiment: <a href=\"https://drossbucket.wordpress.com/2019/08/01/negative-probability/\">https://drossbucket.wordpress.com/2019/08/01/negative-probability/</a>)","favorite_count":"166","retweet_count":"43"},{"created_at":"Thu Aug 01 19:29:40 +0000 2019","id_str":"1157010528595787777","full_text":"I split it into two parts. That first one doesn't require any particular maths or physics background. Second post if you want some equations: <a href=\"https://drossbucket.wordpress.com/2019/08/01/negative-probability-now-with-added-equations/\">https://drossbucket.wordpress.com/2019/08/01/negative-probability-now-with-added-equations/</a>","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Aug 01 19:29:40 +0000 2019","id_str":"1157010526276333570","full_text":"New posts trying to make sense of the idea of negative probabilities. Or, failing that, at least trying to explain how they crop up in quantum physics <a href=\"https://drossbucket.wordpress.com/2019/08/01/negative-probability/\">https://drossbucket.wordpress.com/2019/08/01/negative-probability/</a>","favorite_count":"8","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Mon Jul 29 06:38:18 +0000 2019","id_str":"1155729241046228993","full_text":"Making a lot of diagrams in Inkscape this morning. There are many things I enjoy about Inkscape, but my favourite little feature is that the # key is the shortcut to toggle the grid. You hit a key that looks like a grid and get a grid. Perfect! <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1155729241046228993-EAn5mReWkAUJVzJ.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1155729241046228993-EAn5mReWkAUJVzJ.png\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sun Jul 14 19:22:46 +0000 2019","id_str":"1150485810820583424","full_text":"I think the thread I just posted is the first time ever that I've enjoyed using Twitter as a tool üòÄ Normally it feels like a horrible uphill slog to say anything at all on here so I don't bother. Maybe I'm finally getting the idea!","favorite_count":"11","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sun Jul 14 19:20:13 +0000 2019","id_str":"1150485167384989703","full_text":"Finally, I really like what Poincar√© had to say (in 1905!). Maths instead of language, but the imagery is strikingly similar to Derrida's deserted city. He saw that meaning had to get in from the bottom end too - 'the old intuitive notions of our fathers'. <a href=\"https://www-history.mcs.st-andrews.ac.uk/Extras/Poincare_Intuition.html\">https://www-history.mcs.st-andrews.ac.uk/Extras/Poincare_Intuition.html</a> <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1150485167384989703-D_dYJycW4AItF41.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1150485167384989703-D_dYJycW4AItF41.png\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"20","retweet_count":"2"},{"created_at":"Sun Jul 14 19:20:10 +0000 2019","id_str":"1150485152650473475","full_text":"I think the bottom end without the top end is also a failure. You'd get a sort of unarticulated preconceptual soup with no structure to it. Language stabilises meaning.","favorite_count":"11","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Sun Jul 14 19:20:09 +0000 2019","id_str":"1150485150452592646","full_text":"Derrida seemed to be very alive to the problem, and used resources from phenomenology to try and breathe life into the abandoned city. <br><br>Unfortunately he's unreadable! So I can't tell you whether his solution was any good. ‚òπÔ∏è","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sun Jul 14 19:20:08 +0000 2019","id_str":"1150485146988142593","full_text":"As far as I understand it, structuralism tried to get meaning out of just the top end, the web of relations between terms in language. This doesn't work on its own, there's no there *there* without the bottom end. In 'Force and Signification', Derrida called it a 'deserted city': <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1150485146988142593-D_dYIWuW4AIlg1l.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1150485146988142593-D_dYIWuW4AIlg1l.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"6","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sun Jul 14 19:20:03 +0000 2019","id_str":"1150485127098748929","full_text":"At the top end, words and phrases also activate other words and phrases that are related in some way. This is the top end as these are already packaged into language - it's more conceptual, less direct. <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1150485127098748929-D_dYG4zWwAAoQql.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1150485127098748929-D_dYG4zWwAAoQql.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sun Jul 14 19:19:57 +0000 2019","id_str":"1150485101903585285","full_text":"At the bottom end, meaning grounds out in action, and in the body. This is prelinguistic. Understanding of this goes through Wittgenstein among many others. <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1150485101903585285-D_dYFJxWkAEWEhH.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1150485101903585285-D_dYFJxWkAEWEhH.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sun Jul 14 19:19:50 +0000 2019","id_str":"1150485072480522241","full_text":"Now I understood this already, but Gilchrist makes a further distinction between associations coming in 'from the bottom' and 'from the top', which is new to me. Maybe this isn't an absolute split, but I'm finding the distinction helpful anyway. <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1150485072480522241-D_dYEVsXsAANYfI.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1150485072480522241-D_dYEVsXsAANYfI.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sun Jul 14 19:19:47 +0000 2019","id_str":"1150485057901080581","full_text":"All language drags a string of associations along with it. (How much attention you pay to these is at the heart of the decoupling/contextualising idea.) <br><br>@Meaningness has the BEST terminology for these: <a href=\"https://twitter.com/Meaningness/status/1059189937973551104\">https://twitter.com/Meaningness/status/1059189937973551104</a> <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1150485057901080581-D_dYCziXsAATGPn.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1150485057901080581-D_dYCziXsAATGPn.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"9","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Sun Jul 14 19:19:41 +0000 2019","id_str":"1150485031145672705","full_text":"I've been reading McGilchrist's The Master and his Emissary and can't stop thinking about one section.<br><br>Here's the whole quote. I'll go through each bit below. <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1150485031145672705-D_dX_uKXkAEnTuj.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1150485031145672705-D_dX_uKXkAEnTuj.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"53","retweet_count":"5"},{"created_at":"Sat Jun 29 13:06:16 +0000 2019","id_str":"1144955241022054402","full_text":"Apparently he's a lance corporal. His predecessor got temporarily demoted for trying to headbutt a drummer <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Windsor_(goat)\">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Windsor_(goat)</a> <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1144955241022054402-D-OytXiX4AAlRhw.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1144955241022054402-D-OytXiX4AAlRhw.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Sat Jun 29 13:02:15 +0000 2019","id_str":"1144954231381725185","full_text":"There's an Important Goat in town today <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1144954231381725185-D-OxtayX4AUQytP.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1144954231381725185-D-OxtayX4AUQytP.jpg\"></a></li><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1144954231381725185-D-OxtazXUAAEms_.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1144954231381725185-D-OxtazXUAAEms_.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Fri Jun 28 20:00:51 +0000 2019","id_str":"1144697188636864514","full_text":"@DRMacIver cc @_molten_steel_","favorite_count":"0","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Jun 28 19:53:18 +0000 2019","id_str":"1144695285102387202","full_text":"Finally walked this yesterday! The circuit's now been simplified down to 'only' 28 miles (still more than enough for me) with 45 bridges. <a href=\"https://twitter.com/drossbucket/status/1062444569672011776\">https://twitter.com/drossbucket/status/1062444569672011776</a>","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Jun 24 19:09:47 +0000 2019","id_str":"1143234785323683842","full_text":"@Meaningness @DRMacIver For me at least a lot of this is some kind of unarticulated felt sense that is always worth interrogating - it's surprisingly detailed/subtle compared to my verbal understanding. This is the main reason I started reading Focusing, actually.","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Jun 13 06:00:17 +0000 2019","id_str":"1139049833065586688","full_text":"@Meaningness @mmultiplier Also reminded me that I want to read more Ryckman (the reviewer). Read his Reign of Relativity as an undergrad - mostly beyond me but pointed me to the crazy soup of phenomenological interpretations in GR's early days, rather than the vaguely positivist spirit that won out.","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu May 23 05:23:54 +0000 2019","id_str":"1131430531051204608","full_text":"@Meaningness @vgr @sarahdoingthing e.g. clouds are nebulous (obviously) but not a mess.","favorite_count":"0","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu May 16 14:00:30 +0000 2019","id_str":"1129023822101929985","full_text":"I've stuck my 2018 newsletters up on my website now! Seems like I stop feeling self-conscious about them after a while, so they may as well become public. <a href=\"https://drossbucket.wordpress.com/newsletters/\">https://drossbucket.wordpress.com/newsletters/</a>","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"3"},{"created_at":"Sun Mar 31 20:08:29 +0000 2019","id_str":"1112446589497425920","full_text":"Time for a get-off-Twitter month, haven't had one in a while. See you all in May!","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Jun 03 19:28:21 +0000 2022","id_str":"1532806414019747841","full_text":"Continuing my series of thrilling crowd-pleasing topics with some notes on Husserl's The Origin of Geometry <a href=\"https://lucykeer.com/notebucket/origin-of-geometry-notes/\">https://lucykeer.com/notebucket/origin-of-geometry-notes/</a>","favorite_count":"1","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Jun 02 16:19:17 +0000 2022","id_str":"1532396442693906434","full_text":"55. TIL about the Maple Syrup Strategic Reserve <a href=\"https://twitter.com/etiennefd/